<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does commercial washer repair cost in Los Angeles?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Our commercial diagnostic fee is $120, applied toward the repair once you approve the work. Most commercial washer repairs run between $180 and $500. Drain pump, door lock, lid switch, water inlet valve, or control board replacement is toward the mid-range. Bearing replacement or motor work runs higher. We provide a full written estimate before any work begins."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you repair coin-operated commercial washers?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, we repair the mechanical and electrical systems of coin-operated commercial washers — drain pump, motor, bearings, door lock, water inlet valve, control board, and all standard washer components. For coin acceptor and card reader payment system electronics specifically, we'll assess the issue on-site and let you know whether it's within our scope or requires the payment system vendor. Most coin-op failures are the washer itself, not the payment mechanism."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My commercial washer in an apartment building is not draining — can you come today?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. We dispatch commercial washer calls same day — a shared laundry room in an apartment building with a down washer generates tenant complaints quickly. Call (323) 870-4790 and describe the machine and the symptom. We'll route the call and give you a service window. For multi-machine laundry rooms, describe how many machines are affected so we can bring the appropriate parts."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How often should commercial washers be serviced in Los Angeles?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Every 6 months for moderate-use commercial washers in apartment buildings. Every 3–4 months for high-volume laundromat machines running 10–15 cycles per day. A service visit includes drain pump inspection, door boot/gasket check, bearing condition assessment, water inlet valve test, and control board check for error codes. Regular maintenance prevents the mid-cycle failures that strand a load of laundry and generate tenant complaints."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you repair Speed Queen, Dexter, and Continental Girbau commercial washers?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Speed Queen is the most common commercial washer in LA apartment buildings and laundromats — we carry Speed Queen parts specifically. We also service Dexter, Maytag Commercial, Continental Girbau, UniMac, Wascomat, Electrolux Professional, and Huebsch. For parts-specific service on specialized brands, we'll confirm availability before scheduling."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should I repair or replace my commercial washer?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Commercial washers last 10–15 years with proper maintenance. Under 8 years old, repair almost always makes sense — even a $400 repair on a machine generating $200+ per week in coin revenue pays back in days. Over 12 years old with bearing or motor failure, we'll give you an honest assessment including the cost of a comparable replacement. We'll tell you directly if the repair cost approaches the point where replacement makes more financial sense."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can you service multiple machines in a laundromat on the same visit?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. For laundromats and multi-machine laundry rooms, we prioritize visits to service all affected units on the same trip. When you call, let us know how many machines need service and describe each issue — this allows us to bring the right parts for multiple potential repairs and minimize the number of visits needed. Multi-unit operators can also discuss priority service agreements."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

