</section>

<!-- PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04 — Common Failures</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians diagnose most often in LA commercial washers</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Not Draining / Water Pooling</h3>
        <p>Failed drain pump motor (most common), clogged drain pump filter with debris, or a blocked drain hose. In high-volume laundromat environments, drain pumps accumulate lint, coins, and debris at a rate that makes quarterly pump cleaning standard practice. A washer that won't drain is immediately out of service — customers can't retrieve their laundry.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Not Spinning / Weak Spin</h3>
        <p>Failed drive motor, worn motor coupling (on direct-drive machines), or a drive belt failure (on belt-drive machines). Also: lid switch or door lock failure preventing the spin cycle from initiating. Commercial washers spinning 15+ loads per day wear motor couplings 3–5x faster than residential units — it's a known consumable on high-volume Speed Queens.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Water Leaking</h3>
        <p>Door boot seal failure on front-load machines, water inlet valve leaking when not in use, or a tub bearing seal failure (more serious). On high-traffic laundromat front-loaders, the door boot seal is the most frequently replaced part — door opening and closing 15+ times per day accelerates seal wear significantly faster than residential use.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Won't Start / Dead Machine</h3>
        <p>Control board fault, failed lid switch or door lock preventing cycle initiation, or a tripped thermal overload on the motor. For coin-operated machines: the payment mechanism may be preventing operation even if the washer itself is functional — we'll assess both during the diagnostic visit.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Excessive Noise / Vibration</h3>
        <p>Failing drum bearing — the most expensive commercial washer repair, and the one that announces itself loudest. A bearing failing on a commercial front-loader makes a deep grinding or rumbling sound on spin. Catching it before the bearing seizes completely is the difference between a $300 bearing replacement and a $700+ repair with tub damage.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Error Codes / Stuck in Cycle</h3>
        <p>Modern commercial washers with digital controls display error codes for most failure conditions. We use diagnostic tools to read codes for Speed Queen, Dexter, and Continental Girbau equipment. Common codes indicate water inlet issues, drain failures, motor faults, and sensor problems — the code narrows the diagnosis significantly and reduces diagnostic time.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- COIN-OP SCOPE BLOCK -->
    <div class="coinop-block">
      <div class="c-label">🪙 Coin-Op &amp; Card Payment Systems — Honest Scope</div>
      <h3>What we repair vs. what the payment system vendor handles</h3>
      <p>Coin-operated and card-reader equipped commercial washers have two separate systems: the washer itself (mechanical and electrical), and the payment mechanism (coin acceptor, card reader, mobile payment interface). We repair the washer systems — drain pump, motor, bearings, door lock, water inlet valve, control board. For coin acceptor jams and card reader communication failures, we'll assess on-site and let you know if it's within our scope or requires the payment system vendor or manufacturer. The majority of "coin-op washer failures" we diagnose are the washer, not the payment system — but we'll tell you honestly which it is rather than guess.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- BRANDS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">05 — Brands We Service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Every commercial washer brand running LA laundry rooms</h2>
    <div class="brands-grid">
      <span class="brand-chip">Speed Queen</span>
      <span class="brand-chip">Dexter</span>
      <span class="brand-chip">Maytag Commercial</span>
      <span class="brand-chip">Continental Girbau</span>
      <span class="brand-chip">UniMac</span>
