<!-- RECENT REPAIRS -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">06 — Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Koreatown · 40-Unit Apartment Building · Speed Queen SWNN2SP Front-Load</div>
        <h3>"Washer not draining — door locked with clothes inside, tenants complaining"</h3>
        <p>Failed drain pump motor on a Speed Queen front-load commercial washer in a shared laundry room. The drum had completed the wash cycle but the pump had failed mid-drain, leaving the machine full of water with the door locked (door lock disengages only when the drum is empty per the safety interlock). Three tenants had been waiting for their laundry for hours when the property manager called.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Accessed pump through the front service panel, confirmed pump motor failure by testing resistance — open circuit. Replaced with OEM Speed Queen drain pump motor (carried on van). Manually drained the tub, released door lock, returned stranded laundry to tenants. Machine operational and ran through a full test cycle before we left. Property manager enrolled in a 6-month preventive maintenance contract for the building's three laundry machines.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Hollywood · 15-Machine Laundromat · Dexter T-400 Top-Load Washers (3)</div>
        <h3>"Three machines down same week — two not spinning, one leaking"</h3>
        <p>Three simultaneous failures at a busy Hollywood laundromat — two Dexter T-400 top-loaders with failed motor couplings (the direct-drive coupling between motor and transmission wears out in high-cycle-count machines) and one with a water inlet valve leak. The operator had been losing roughly $150–$200 per day in combined machine revenue during the week they'd been down, waiting for a service call.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced motor couplings on both non-spinning machines — carried Dexter motor coupling kits on the van, a standard consumable for high-volume laundromats. Replaced water inlet valve on the leaking machine. All three operational within 3 hours of arrival. Operator had been losing $1,050–$1,400 in estimated revenue during the 7-day downtime — the three repairs combined cost $840. Discussed a quarterly maintenance contract to prevent simultaneous failures. Enrolled immediately.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">West Hollywood · Boutique Hotel · Maytag Commercial MHN33 Front-Load</div>
        <h3>"Grinding noise on spin cycle for two weeks — now won't spin at all"</h3>
        <p>Rear drum bearing failure on a Maytag Commercial front-load in the hotel's on-premises laundry room. The bearing had been failing progressively — the grinding noise during spin was the bearing under load, and the hotel staff had been noting it but hadn't called for service. By the time we arrived, the bearing had seized and the drum wouldn't spin under motor load, stalling the machine with laundry inside.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Disassembled tub to access rear bearing assembly. Found bearing completely seized and inner race cracked — consistent with extended operation after bearing failure onset. Replaced bearing and front and rear tub seals simultaneously. Rebuilt and tested through 3 full spin cycles before reassembly. Full repair including tub seal replacement: $485. Had the bearing been addressed at the first sign of grinding (the typical bearing replacement in early failure is $280–$340), the hotel would have saved $145 and avoided 2 weeks of degraded laundry capacity.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Silver Lake · 24-Unit Apartment Building · Speed Queen Commercial SWFT71WN</div>
        <h3>"Washer shows error code E5 — stopped mid-cycle, won't restart"</h3>
        <p>Error code E5 on a Speed Queen commercial front-load indicates a door lock/latch fault — the door lock assembly had failed, preventing the machine from confirming the door was secured and halting the cycle mid-wash. The machine was holding water and locked. Residents were frustrated; one had already emailed the property manager about the situation.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Diagnosed door lock assembly failure via the error code and confirmed with electrical testing — door lock solenoid coil had failed open. Replaced door lock assembly with OEM Speed Queen part (carried on van). Cleared the error code, drained the machine, ran through a complete test cycle with simulated load. Machine operational within 75 minutes of arrival. Advised property manager on the error code reference for Speed Queen commercial units — knowing what E5 means helps catch it faster next time rather than waiting until multiple tenants call.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

